entries.meaning: (obsolete) A method of fishing using a line with several hooks fastened to it along with a lead weight so that the hooks sit on the bottom.

verbs.description: grabble (third-person singular simple present grabbles, present participle grabbling, simple past and past participle grabbled)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To search with one's hands and fingers; to attempt to grasp something.
examples: Synonyms: fumble, grope, grubble, root, rummage; see also Thesaurus:feel around

entries.meaning: (intransitive, obsolete) To search in a similar way using an implement.
examples: […]  he proposes to spend the Afternoon at the Out-side of the Rock, in viewing the Sea, and looking for Oysters; so takes in his Hand his long Staff to grabble in Holes  […]

entries.meaning: (transitive) To touch (someone) with one's hands or fingers, sometimes in a sexual way.
examples: Synonyms: feel up, fondle, grope; see also Thesaurus:fondle

entries.meaning: (transitive) To pick (something or someone) up hastily, roughly or clumsily.
(transitive) To attempt to grab; to grasp at (something).
examples: Synonyms: clutch, grip; see also Thesaurus:grasp

entries.meaning: (transitive) To pull, lift or dig (something) (out of the ground) by searching with one's hands and fingers.
(transitive, obsolete) To lift (something) out in a similar way using an implement.
examples: […]  set all these togither on the fire, & boile them till the wine and water be consumed, and that the flesh and bones be separated a sunder, that you may with a paire of tongs grabble out the bones from the rest, thus let it be taken off and pressed through a piece of canuas, and keepe it to your use.

entries.meaning: (transitive, intransitive, now Southeastern US) To catch fish by reaching into the water with one's hand.
(transitive, intransitive, obsolete) To fish on the grabble.
examples: It was just after such a day that I grabbled fifty of the best salmon I ever saw—all fresh run from the sea.

entries.meaning: (transitive, intransitive) To utter inarticulate sounds, often quickly and loudly; to say (something) quickly, idly or foolishly.
(intransitive, obsolete) To lie prostrate; to sprawl on the ground.
